article.description: Sophia Young scored 15 points and Steffanie Blackmon added 14 to lead Baylor (No. 9 ESPN/USA Today, No. 6 AP) to an 89-62 victory over Florida.
article.headline: Young, Blackmon combine for 29 points
article.linkText: Second-half surge lifts Baylor past Florida
article.story:
WACO, Texas (AP) -- Baylor played its sloppiest game of the season on Sunday. It hardly mattered.

The Lady Bears (No. 9 ESPN/USA Today, No. 6 AP) blew out the Florida Gators 89-62, despite committing a season-high 26 turnovers.

Baylor coach Kim Mulkey-Robertson couldn't complain -- not after the team came within two points of its season high.

"This team is playing good basketball," Mulkey-Robertson said. "As ugly and as sloppy as we were, we won by 25, we played everybody on the bench and it's a win."

Five players scored in double figures for Baylor (9-1), which shot 53.7 percent. Sophia Young led the scoring with 15 points and Steffanie Blackmon added 14. Emily Niemann scored 13, Abiola Wabara 12 and Latoya Wyatt 11.

"It was good (getting the balanced scoring)," Blackmon said. "Going into conference play, it helps our team to get more production from the guards."

Brittany Davis led Florida (6-3) with 16 points and Tamia Williams added 14. The Gators only made 26.9 of their shots.

Baylor opened the second half with nine straight points to take a 54-33 lead over the Gators with just under 16 minutes left. Florida never got closer than 16 points thereafter.

"Baylor is ranked sixth in the country for a reason," Florida coach Carolyn Peck said. "We had some opportunities and made some runs. But this team by no means should drop their heads."

Behind 3-pointers by Wyatt and Niemann, Baylor jumped out to a 9-1 lead. The Lady Bears upped the margin to 21-6 with just under 12 minutes remaining.

Paced by seven points from Davis, Florida chipped away and narrowed the gap to 27-23 at the 6:30 mark. But Baylor regrouped, and Young's five straight points fueled an 8-0 run for a 35-23 lead.

Baylor led 45-33 at the half with Young and Niemann scoring 10 points apiece.
